	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Thu, Jan 10th 9:37 AM 2002</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent<span id=notbold>[2.67]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>And ya posted anon too. Now there's a shocker. Here's the deal anon, casters mele. Deal. It doesn't come into play often, nor should it, but there are times when we land one nuke too many and end up with a very upset monster looking to make us its next victim.<br><br>Granted, pure casters shouldn't be looking to mele trakk, nor any of the major mobs in the game. So if yer lvl 60ish and mainly raiding, you're probably not going to have much use for mele.<br><br>Granted, casters aren't MADE to be tanks, but there are times when we get forced into the role. <br><br>Casters won't tank a mob to death solo, but they CAN take a few hits here and there and not cave. Particularly if they've been in enough actual combat to have semi-decent defence. That mage ya got all the way up to lvl 16.. did ya ever have a situation where yer pet was almost dead? willing to bet ya did. Now a mob will always target the pet's summoner over the pet IF the summoner is in range. That means you can wade in, take a few hits for your pet, and wade right back out again without having to worry about aggro being on ya.<br><br>This happens frequently. Particularly nasty if yer near oom and don't have enough for a pet healing spell. Now ya COULD med through and hope to god you get enough to heal the pet before it dies, or you can hop in, mele for a couple hits, and THEN med. Chances are if yer pet dies, you'll still have about the same odds of being able to run, however, you just considerably upped your chances of surviving the encounter, because while you were taking a beating, your pet wasn't. And you BOTH were dealing damage. Look at about half your life bar as an extention of your pet's. If yer gonna be in range to take hits, you might as well mele. If yer gonna be meleing, you might as well be passable at it. There's nothing that says you can't be excellent at casting, yet still have a high skill in a weapon, decent offence and decent defence.<br><br>Now think group for a second. If you have a caster, you always gotta watch out for overnuking. However, there are times when you WANT aggro. Particularly on an overpull and/or if someone, like for instance the cleric who can heal your ass, is about to die. Just nuke as fast as you can on the offending mob, catch the aggro, and mele till a tank can peel it off you.<br><br>It doesn't apply to all situations by any means, but it is an available tatic, and it does have it's uses. Way I see it, if you have something that gives you an advantage, even an extra 20 damage per thwak from a caster in mele range between casts, then use that advantage. It works. IF the caster in question knows what they're doing.<br><br>But since you have 3 lvl 51 characters and are obviously god's gift to EQ, I'm sure you already knew all that.<br><br>You don't want a caster who knows when to mele at yer back? Just fine by me. Chances are if you're too dumb to use what advantages are presented you, I don't want you at my front.<br><br><br>Faelawen Starfyre, The Mad Mage of Povar<br><br><em id=fs8>Edited, Thu Jan 10 09:40:53 2002</em><br>&nbsp;<br></td></tr>
